      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "9ddba40bfa8f09651a9b7a598de8ecfd",
      "text": "# Arable and haymeadow commons"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "52889fed1593c8370fdb33e06115fe3f",
      "text": "Surviving commons are almost all pasture, but in earlier times, arable ([[arable land]]) farming and [[hay]]making were significant, with strips of land in the common arable fields ([[Open field system]]) and common haymeadows assigned annually by lot ([[Sortition]]).  When not in use for those purposes, such commons were [[graze]]d.  Examples include the common arable fields around the village of Laxton ([[Laxton, Nottinghamshire#Open Fields]]) in Nottinghamshire, and a common meadow at [[North Meadow, Cricklade]]."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7f3f5b4c6382360f9236b49107f95128",
      "text": "# Lammas rights"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ea6486c34ccdde69f9d6397c6b7afa2b",
      "text": "''Lammas rights'' entitled commoners to pasture following the harvest, between [[Lammas]] day, 12 August (N.S. ([[Old Style and New Style dates]])), to 6 April, even if they did not have other rights to the land. Such rights sometimes had the effect of preventing enclosure and building development on agricultural land.[ The Historical Background]"
    },
